# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: vector-autoregression
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] In statistics, an **autoregressive** (**AR**) **model** is a modelled representation of a type of random process.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] It can be used to describe time-varying processes from many natural and artificial sources.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] The model specifies output variables that are dependent linearly on their own previous values on a stochastic basis.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] The model is in the form of a stochastic difference equation (or recurrence relation) which should not be confused with a differential equation.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] Another important extension is the time-varying autoregressive (TVAR) model, where the autoregressive coefficients are allowed to change over time to model evolving or non-stationary processes.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] TVAR models are widely applied in cases where the underlying dynamics of the system are not constant, such as in sensors time series modelling, climate science, economics and finance (as econometrics), signal processing, telecommunications, radar systems, and biological signals.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] Unlike the moving-average (MA) model, the autoregressive model is not always stationary; non-stationarity can arise either due to the presence of a unit root or due to time-varying model parameters, as in time-varying autoregressive models.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] Large language models are called autoregressive, but they are not a classical autoregressive model in this sense because they are not linear.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] The notation $AR(p)$ indicates an autoregressive model of order *p*.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] where $\varphi _{1},\ldots ,\varphi _{p}$ are the *parameters* of the model, and $\varepsilon _{t}$ is white noise.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] An autoregressive model can thus be viewed as the output of an all-pole infinite impulse response filter whose input is white noise.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] Some parameter constraints are necessary for the model to remain weak-sense stationary.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] For example, processes in the AR(1) model with $|\varphi _{1}|\geq 1$ are not stationary.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] More generally, for an AR(*p*) model to be weak-sense stationary, the roots of the polynomial $\Phi (z):=\textstyle 1-\sum _{i=1}^{p}\varphi _{i}z^{i}$ must lie outside the unit circle, i.e., each (complex) root $z_{i}$ must satisfy $|z_{i}|>1$ (see pages 89,92 ).
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] In an AR process, a one-time shock affects values of the evolving variable infinitely far into the future.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] A non-zero value for $\varepsilon _{t}$ at say time *t*=1 affects $X_{1}$ by the amount $\varepsilon _{1}$ .
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] Then by the AR equation for $X_{2}$ in terms of $X_{1}$ , this affects $X_{2}$ by the amount $\varphi _{1}\varepsilon _{1}$ .
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] Then by the AR equation for $X_{3}$ in terms of $X_{2}$ , this affects $X_{3}$ by the amount $\varphi _{1}^{2}\varepsilon _{1}$ .
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] Continuing this process shows that the effect of $\varepsilon _{1}$ never ends, although if the process is stationary then the effect diminishes toward zero in the limit.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] Because each shock affects *X* values infinitely far into the future from when they occur, any given value *X**t* is affected by shocks occurring infinitely far into the past.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] When the polynomial division on the right side is carried out, the polynomial in the backshift operator applied to $\varepsilon _{t}$ has an infinite order—that is, an infinite number of lagged values of $\varepsilon _{t}$ appear on the right side of the equation.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] where *B* is the backshift operator, where $\varphi (\cdot )$ is the function defining the autoregression, and where $\varphi _{k}$ are the coefficients in the autoregression.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] The formula is valid only if all the roots have multiplicity 1.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] The autocorrelation function of an AR(*p*) process is a sum of decaying exponentials.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] The simplest AR process is AR(0), which has no dependence between the terms.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] Only the error/innovation/noise term contributes to the output of the process, so in the figure, AR(0) corresponds to white noise.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] For an AR(1) process with a positive $\varphi$ , only the previous term in the process and the noise term contribute to the output.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] If $\varphi$ is close to 0, then the process still looks like white noise, but as $\varphi$ approaches 1, the output gets a larger contribution from the previous term relative to the noise.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] This results in a "smoothing" or integration of the output, similar to a low pass filter.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] For an AR(2) process, the previous two terms and the noise term contribute to the output.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] If both $\varphi _{1}$ and $\varphi _{2}$ are positive, the output will resemble a low pass filter, with the high frequency part of the noise decreased.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] If $\varphi _{1}$ is positive while $\varphi _{2}$ is negative, then the process favors changes in sign between terms of the process.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] This can be linked to edge detection or detection of change in direction.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] An AR(1) process is given by: $X_{t}=\varphi X_{t-1}+\varepsilon _{t}\,$ where $\varepsilon _{t}$ is a white noise process with zero mean and constant variance $\sigma _{\varepsilon }^{2}$ .
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] (Note: The subscript on $\varphi _{1}$ has been dropped.) The process is weak-sense stationary if $|\varphi |<1$ since it is obtained as the output of a stable filter whose input is white noise.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] where $\sigma _{\varepsilon }$ is the standard deviation of $\varepsilon _{t}$ .
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] and then by noticing that the quantity above is a stable fixed point of this relation.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] It can be seen that the autocovariance function decays with a decay time (also called time constant) of $\tau =1/(1-\varphi )$ .
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] The spectral density function is the Fourier transform of the autocovariance function.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] This expression is periodic due to the discrete nature of the $X_{j}$ , which is manifested as the cosine term in the denominator.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] where $\gamma =1/\tau$ is the angular frequency associated with the decay time $\tau$ .
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] An alternative expression for $X_{t}$ can be derived by first substituting $\varphi X_{t-2}+\varepsilon _{t-1}$ for $X_{t-1}$ in the defining equation.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] It is seen that $X_{t}$ is white noise convolved with the $\varphi ^{k}$ kernel plus the constant mean.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] If the white noise $\varepsilon _{t}$ is a Gaussian process then $X_{t}$ is also a Gaussian process.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] In other cases, the central limit theorem indicates that $X_{t}$ will be approximately normally distributed when $\varphi$ is close to one.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] For $\varepsilon _{t}=0$ , the process $X_{t}=\varphi X_{t-1}$ will be a geometric progression (*exponential* growth or decay).
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] In this case, the solution can be found analytically: $X_{t}=a\varphi ^{t}$ whereby a is an unknown constant (initial condition).
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] The AR(1) model is the discrete-time analogy of the continuous Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] It is therefore sometimes useful to understand the properties of the AR(1) model cast in an equivalent form.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] The partial autocorrelation of an AR(p) process equals zero at lags larger than *p*, so the appropriate maximum lag *p* is the one after which the partial autocorrelations are all zero.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] There are many ways to estimate the coefficients, such as the ordinary least squares procedure or method of moments (through Yule–Walker equations).
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] It is based on parameters $\varphi _{i}$ where *i* = 1, ..., *p*.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] There is a direct correspondence between these parameters and the covariance function of the process, and this correspondence can be inverted to determine the parameters from the autocorrelation function (which is itself obtained from the covariances).
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] This is done using the Yule–Walker equations.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] The Yule–Walker equations, named for Udny Yule and Gilbert Walker, are the following set of equations.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] Here $\gamma _{m}$ is the autocovariance function of Xt, $\sigma _{\varepsilon }$ is the standard deviation of the input noise process, and $\delta _{m,0}$ is the Kronecker delta function.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] An alternative formulation is in terms of the autocorrelation function.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] The AR parameters are determined by the first *p*+1 elements $\rho (\tau )$ of the autocorrelation function.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] The above equations (the Yule–Walker equations) provide several routes to estimating the parameters of an AR(*p*) model, by replacing the theoretical covariances with estimated values.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] but the reasoning behind this applies to the use of any set of estimated AR parameters.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] Compared to the estimation scheme using only the forward prediction equations, different estimates of the autocovariances are produced, and the estimates have different stability properties.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] Other possible approaches to estimation include maximum likelihood estimation.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] Substantial differences in the results of these approaches can occur if the observed series is short, or if the process is close to non-stationarity.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] The terms involving square roots are all real in the case of complex poles since they exist only when $\varphi _{2}<0$ .
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] The process is non-stationary when the poles are on or outside the unit circle, or equivalently when the characteristic roots are on or inside the unit circle.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] The process is stable when the poles are strictly within the unit circle (roots strictly outside the unit circle), or equivalently when the coefficients are in the triangle $-1\leq \varphi _{2}\leq 1-|\varphi _{1}|$ .
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] The impulse response of a system is the change in an evolving variable in response to a change in the value of a shock term *k* periods earlier, as a function of *k*.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] Since the AR model is a special case of the vector autoregressive model, the computation of the impulse response in vector autoregression#impulse response applies here.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] have been estimated, the autoregression can be used to forecast an arbitrary number of periods into the future.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] The output of the autoregressive equation is the forecast for the first unobserved period.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] Then for future periods the same procedure is used, each time using one more forecast value on the right side of the predictive equation until, after *p* predictions, all *p* right-side values are predicted values from preceding steps.
[src:vector-autoregression/autoregressive-model] Each of the last three can be quantified and combined to give a confidence interval for the *n*-step-ahead predictions; the confidence interval will become wider as *n* increases because of the use of an increasing number of estimated values for the right-side variables.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] The **Granger causality test** is a statistical hypothesis test for determining whether one time series is useful in forecasting another, first proposed in 1969.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] Ordinarily, regressions reflect "mere" correlations, but Clive Granger argued that causality in economics could be tested for by measuring the ability to predict the future values of a time series using prior values of another time series.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] Since the question of "true causality" is deeply philosophical, and because of the post hoc ergo propter hoc fallacy of assuming that one thing preceding another can be used as a proof of causation, econometricians assert that the Granger test finds only "predictive causality".
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] Using the term "causality" alone is a misnomer, as Granger-causality is better described as "precedence", or, as Granger himself later claimed in 1977, "temporally related".
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] A time series *X* is said to Granger-cause *Y* if it can be shown, usually through a series of t-tests and F-tests on lagged values of *X* (and with lagged values of *Y* also included), that those *X* values provide statistically significant information about future values of *Y*.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] Granger also stressed that some studies using "Granger causality" testing in areas outside economics reached "ridiculous" conclusions.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] "Of course, many ridiculous papers appeared", he said in his Nobel lecture.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] However, it remains a popular method for causality analysis in time series due to its computational simplicity.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] The original definition of Granger causality does not account for latent confounding effects and does not capture instantaneous and non-linear causal relationships, though several extensions have been proposed to address these issues.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] We say that a variable *X* that evolves over time *Granger-causes* another evolving variable *Y* if predictions of the value of *Y* based on its own past values *and* on the past values of *X* are better than predictions of *Y* based only on *Y'*s own past values.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] The cause has *unique* information about the future values of its effect.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] where $\mathbb {P}$ refers to probability, A is an arbitrary non-empty set, and ${\mathcal {I}}(t)$ and ${\mathcal {I}}_{-X}(t)$ respectively denote the information available as of time t in the entire universe, and that in the modified universe in which X is excluded.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] If the above hypothesis is accepted, we say that X Granger-causes Y .
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] If a time series is a stationary process, the test is performed using the level values of two (or more) variables.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] If the variables are non-stationary, then the test is done using first (or higher) differences.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] The number of lags to be included is usually chosen using an information criterion, such as the Akaike information criterion or the Schwarz information criterion.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] Any particular lagged value of one of the variables is retained in the regression if (1) it is significant according to a t-test, and (2) it and the other lagged values of the variable jointly add explanatory power to the model according to an F-test.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] Then the null hypothesis of no Granger causality is not rejected if and only if no lagged values of an explanatory variable have been retained in the regression.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] In practice it may be found that neither variable Granger-causes the other, or that each of the two variables Granger-causes the other.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] Let *y* and *x* be stationary time series.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] One retains in this regression all lagged values of *x* that are individually significant according to their t-statistics, provided that collectively they add explanatory power to the regression according to an F-test (whose null hypothesis is no explanatory power jointly added by the *x'*s).
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] In the notation of the above augmented regression, *p* is the shortest, and *q* is the longest, lag length for which the lagged value of *x* is significant.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] The null hypothesis that *x* does not Granger-cause *y* is not rejected if and only if no lagged values of *x* are retained in the regression.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] Multivariate Granger causality analysis is usually performed by fitting a vector autoregressive model (VAR) to the time series.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] In particular, let $X(t)\in \mathbb {R} ^{d\times 1}$ for $t=1,\ldots ,T$ be a d -dimensional multivariate time series.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] where $\varepsilon (t)$ is a white Gaussian random vector, and $A_{\tau }$ is a matrix for every $\tau$ .
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] A time series $X_{i}$ is called a Granger cause of another time series $X_{j}$ , if at least one of the elements $A_{\tau }(j,i)$ for $\tau =1,\ldots ,L$ is significantly larger than zero (in absolute value).
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] The above linear methods are appropriate for testing Granger causality in the mean.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] However they are not able to detect Granger causality in higher moments, e.g., in the variance.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] Non-parametric tests for Granger causality are designed to address this problem.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] The definition of Granger causality in these tests is general and does not involve any modelling assumptions, such as a linear autoregressive model.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] The non-parametric tests for Granger causality can be used as diagnostic tools to build better parametric models including higher order moments and/or non-linearity.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] As its name implies, Granger causality is not necessarily true causality.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] If both *X* and *Y* are driven by a common third process with different lags, one might still fail to reject the alternative hypothesis of Granger causality.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] Yet, manipulation of one of the variables would not change the other.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] Indeed, the Granger-causality tests are designed to handle pairs of variables, and may produce misleading results when the true relationship involves three or more variables.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] Having said this, it has been argued that given a probabilistic view of causation, Granger causality can be considered true causality in that sense, especially when Reichenbach's "screening off" notion of probabilistic causation is taken into account.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] Other possible sources of misguiding test results are: (1) not frequent enough or too frequent sampling, (2) nonlinear causal relationship, (3) time series nonstationarity and nonlinearity and (4) existence of rational expectations.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] A similar test involving more variables can be applied with vector autoregression.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] A method for Granger causality has been developed that is not sensitive to deviations from the assumption that the error term is normally distributed.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] This method is especially useful in financial economics, since many financial variables are non-normally distributed.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] Recently, asymmetric causality testing has been suggested in the literature in order to separate the causal impact of positive changes from the negative ones.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] An extension of Granger (non-)causality testing to panel data is also available.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] A modified Granger causality test based on the GARCH (generalized auto-regressive conditional heteroscedasticity) type of integer-valued time series models is available in many areas.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] The extension of Granger causality to incorporate its dynamic, time-varying nature allows for a more nuanced understanding of how causal relationships in time-series data evolve over time.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] The methodology uses recursive techniques such as the Forward Expanding (FE), Rolling (RO), and Recursive Evolving (RE) windows to overcome the limitations of traditional Granger causality tests and understand changes in causal relationships across different periods.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] A central aspect of this methodology is the 'tvgc' command in Stata.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] Empirical applications, such as data involving transaction fees and economic sub-systems on Ethereum, highlight the dynamic nature of economic relationships over time.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] A long-held belief about neural function maintained that different areas of the brain were task specific; that the structural connectivity local to a certain area somehow dictated the function of that piece.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] Collecting work that has been performed over many years, there has been a move to a different, network-centric approach to describing information flow in the brain.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] Explanation of function is beginning to include the concept of networks existing at different levels and throughout different locations in the brain.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] The behavior of these networks can be described by non-deterministic processes that are evolving through time.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] That is to say that given the same input stimulus, you will not get the same output from the network.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] The dynamics of these networks are governed by probabilities so we treat them as stochastic (random) processes so that we can capture these kinds of dynamics between different areas of the brain.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] Recently Granger causality has been applied to address some of these issues.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] Put plainly, one examines how to best predict the future of a neuron: using either the entire ensemble or the entire ensemble except a certain target neuron.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] If the prediction is made worse by excluding the target neuron, then we say it has a "g-causal" relationship with the current neuron.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] Previous Granger-causality methods could only operate on continuous-valued data so the analysis of neural spike train recordings involved transformations that ultimately altered the stochastic properties of the data, indirectly altering the validity of the conclusions that could be drawn from it.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] In 2011, however, a new general-purpose Granger-causality framework was proposed that could directly operate on any modality, including neural-spike trains.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] Neural spike train data can be modeled as a point-process.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] A temporal point process is a stochastic time-series of binary events that occurs in continuous time.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] It can only take on two values at each point in time, indicating whether or not an event has actually occurred.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] This type of binary-valued representation of information suits the activity of neural populations because a single neuron's action potential has a typical waveform.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] In this way, what carries the actual information being output from a neuron is the occurrence of a "spike", as well as the time between successive spikes.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] Using this approach one could abstract the flow of information in a neural-network to be simply the spiking times for each neuron through an observation period.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] One of the simplest types of neural-spiking models is the Poisson process.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] This however, is limited in that it is memory-less.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] It does not account for any spiking history when calculating the current probability of firing.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] Neurons, however, exhibit a fundamental (biophysical) history dependence by way of its relative and absolute refractory periods.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] To address this, a conditional intensity function is used to represent the probability of a neuron spiking, conditioned on its own history.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] The conditional intensity function expresses the instantaneous firing probability and implicitly defines a complete probability model for the point process.
[src:vector-autoregression/granger-causality] So if this unit time is taken small enough to ensure that only one spike could occur in that time window, then our conditional intensity function completely specifies the probability that a given neuron will fire in a certain time.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] In signal processing and control theory, the **impulse response**, or **impulse response function** (**IRF**), of a dynamic system is its output when presented with a brief input signal, called an impulse (δ(*t*)).
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] More generally, an impulse response is the reaction of any dynamic system in response to some external change.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] In both cases, the impulse response describes the reaction of the system as a function of time (or possibly as a function of some other independent variable that parameterizes the dynamic behavior of the system).
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] In all these cases, the dynamic system and its impulse response may be actual physical objects, or may be mathematical systems of equations describing such objects.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] Since the impulse function contains all frequencies (see the Fourier transform of the Dirac delta function, showing infinite frequency bandwidth that the Dirac delta function has), the impulse response defines the response of a linear time-invariant system for all frequencies.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] Mathematically, how the impulse is described depends on whether the system is modeled in discrete or continuous time.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] The impulse can be modeled as a Dirac delta function for continuous-time systems, or as the discrete unit sample function for discrete-time systems.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] The Dirac delta represents the limiting case of a pulse made very short in time while maintaining its area or integral (thus giving an infinitely high peak).
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] While this is impossible in any real system, it is a useful idealization.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] In Fourier analysis theory, such an impulse comprises equal portions of all possible excitation frequencies, which makes it a convenient test probe.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] Any system in a large class known as *linear, time-invariant* (LTI) is completely characterized by its impulse response.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] That is, for any input, the output can be calculated in terms of the input and the impulse response.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] (See LTI system theory.) The impulse response of a linear transformation is the image of Dirac's delta function under the transformation, analogous to the fundamental solution of a partial differential operator.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] It is usually easier to analyze systems using transfer functions as opposed to impulse responses.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] The transfer function is the Laplace transform of the impulse response.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] The Laplace transform of a system's output may be determined by the multiplication of the transfer function with the input's Laplace transform in the complex plane, also known as the frequency domain.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] An inverse Laplace transform of this result will yield the output in the time domain.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] To determine an output directly in the time domain requires the convolution of the input with the impulse response.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] When the transfer function and the Laplace transform of the input are known, this convolution may be more complicated than the alternative of multiplying two functions in the frequency domain.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] The impulse response, considered as a Green's function, can be thought of as an "influence function": how a point of input influences output.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] In practice, it is not possible to perturb a system with a perfect impulse.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] One can use a brief pulse as a first approximation.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] Limitations of this approach include the duration of the pulse and its magnitude.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] The response can be close, compared to the ideal case, provided the pulse is short enough.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] Additionally, in many systems, a pulse of large intensity may drive the system into the nonlinear regime.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] Other methods exist to construct an impulse response.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] The impulse response can be calculated from the input and output of a system driven with a pseudo-random sequence, such as maximum length sequences.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] Another approach is to take a sine sweep measurement and process the result to get the impulse response.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] Impulse response loudspeaker testing was first developed in the 1970s.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] Loudspeakers suffer from phase inaccuracy (delayed frequencies) which can be caused by passive crossovers, resonance, cone momentum, the internal volume, and vibrating enclosure panels.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] The impulse response can be used to indicate when such inaccuracies can be improved by different materials, enclosures or crossovers.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] Loudspeakers have a physical limit to their power output, thus the input amplitude must be limited to maintain linearity.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] This limitation led to the use of inputs like maximum length sequences in obtaining the impulse response.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] Impulse response analysis is a major facet of radar, ultrasound imaging, and many areas of digital signal processing.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] An interesting example is found in broadband internet connections.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] Digital subscriber line service providers use adaptive equalization to compensate for signal distortion and interference from using copper phone lines for transmission.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] In control theory the impulse response is the response of a system to a Dirac delta input.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] This proves useful in the analysis of dynamic systems; the Laplace transform of the delta function is 1, so the impulse response is equivalent to the inverse Laplace transform of the system's transfer function.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] In acoustic and audio settings, impulse responses can be used to capture the acoustic characteristics of many things.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] The reverb at a location, the body of an instrument, certain analog audio equipment, and amplifiers are all emulated by impulse responses.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] The impulse is convolved with a dry signal in software, often to create the effect of a physical recording.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] Various packages containing impulse responses from specific locations are available online.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] In economics, and especially in contemporary macroeconomic modeling, impulse response functions are used to describe how the economy reacts over time to exogenous impulses, which economists usually call shocks, and are often modeled in the context of a vector autoregression.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] Impulse response functions describe the reaction of endogenous macroeconomic variables such as output, consumption, investment, and employment at the time of the shock and over subsequent points in time.
[src:vector-autoregression/impulse-response] Recently, asymmetric impulse response functions have been suggested in the literature that separate the impact of a positive shock from a negative one.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] In mathematics and statistics, a **stationary process** (also called a **strict/strictly stationary process** or **strong/strongly stationary process**) is a stochastic process whose statistical properties, such as mean and variance, do not change over time.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] More formally, the joint probability distribution of the process remains the same when shifted in time.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] This implies that the process is statistically consistent across different time periods.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] Because many statistical procedures in time series analysis assume stationarity, non-stationary data are frequently transformed to achieve stationarity before analysis.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] A common cause of non-stationarity is a trend in the mean, which can be due to either a unit root or a deterministic trend.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] In the case of a unit root, stochastic shocks have permanent effects, and the process is not mean-reverting.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] With a deterministic trend, the process is called trend-stationary, and shocks have only transitory effects, with the variable tending towards a deterministically evolving mean.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] A trend-stationary process is not strictly stationary but can be made stationary by removing the trend.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] Similarly, processes with unit roots can be made stationary through differencing.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] Another type of non-stationary process, distinct from those with trends, is a cyclostationary process, which exhibits cyclical variations over time.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] Strict stationarity, as defined above, can be too restrictive for many applications.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] Therefore, other forms of stationarity, such as **wide-sense stationarity** or **⁠ N ⁠th-order stationarity**, are often used.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] The definitions for different kinds of stationarity are not consistent among different authors (see Other terminology).
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] Since $\tau$ does not affect ⁠ $F_{X}(\cdot )$ ⁠, $F_{X}$ is independent of time.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] White noise is the simplest example of a stationary process.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] An example of a discrete-time stationary process where the sample space is also discrete (so that the random variable may take one of ⁠ N ⁠ possible values) is a Bernoulli scheme.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] Other examples of a discrete-time stationary process with continuous sample space include some autoregressive and moving average processes that are both subsets of the autoregressive moving average model.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] Models with a non-trivial autoregressive component may be either stationary or non-stationary, depending on the parameter values, and important non-stationary special cases are where unit roots exist in the model.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] Then $\left\{X_{t}\right\}$ is a stationary time series, for which realisations consist of a series of constant values, with a different constant value for each realisation.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] A law of large numbers does not apply on this case, as the limiting value of an average from a single realisation takes the random value determined by ⁠ Y ⁠, rather than taking the expected value of ⁠ Y ⁠.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] The time average of $X_{t}$ does not converge since the process is not ergodic.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] Then $\left\{X_{t}\right\}$ is strictly stationary since (⁠ $(t+Y)$ ⁠ modulo ⁠ $2\pi$ ⁠) follows the same uniform distribution as Y for any ⁠ t ⁠.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] Keep in mind that a weakly white noise is not necessarily strictly stationary.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] So $\{z_{t}\}$ is a white noise in the weak sense (the mean and cross-covariances are zero, and the variances are all the same), however it is not strictly stationary.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] In **Eq.1**, the distribution of n samples of the stochastic process must be equal to the distribution of the samples shifted in time *for all* ⁠ n ⁠. ⁠ N ⁠th-order stationarity is a weaker form of stationarity where this is only requested for all n up to a certain order ⁠ N ⁠.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] A weaker form of stationarity commonly employed in signal processing is known as **weak-sense stationarity**, **wide-sense stationarity (WSS)**, or **covariance stationarity**.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] WSS random processes only require that 1st moment (i.e. the mean) and autocovariance do not vary with respect to time and that the 2nd moment is finite for all times.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] Any strictly stationary process that has a finite mean and covariance is also WSS.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] The first property implies that the mean function $m_{X}(t)$ must be constant.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] The second property implies that the autocovariance function depends only on the *difference* between $t_{1}$ and $t_{2}$ and only needs to be indexed by one variable rather than two variables.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] The third property says that the second moments must be finite for any time ⁠ t ⁠.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] The main advantage of wide-sense stationarity is that it places the time-series in the context of Hilbert spaces.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] Let ⁠ H ⁠ be the Hilbert space generated by ⁠ $\{x(t)\}$ ⁠ (that is, the closure of the set of all linear combinations of these random variables in the Hilbert space of all square-integrable random variables on the given probability space).
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] By the positive definiteness of the autocovariance function, it follows from Bochner's theorem that there exists a positive measure $\mu$ on the real line such that ⁠ H ⁠ is isomorphic to the Hilbert subspace of ⁠ $L^{2}(\mu )$ ⁠ generated by ⁠ $\{e^{-2\pi i\xi \cdot t}\}$ ⁠.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] where the integral on the right-hand side is interpreted in a suitable (Riemann) sense.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] The same result holds for a discrete-time stationary process, with the spectral measure now defined on the unit circle.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] When processing WSS random signals with linear, time-invariant (LTI) filters, it is helpful to think of the correlation function as a linear operator.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] Since it is a circulant operator (depends only on the difference between the two arguments), its eigenfunctions are the Fourier complex exponentials.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] Additionally, since the eigenfunctions of LTI operators are also complex exponentials, LTI processing of WSS random signals is highly tractable—all computations can be performed in the frequency domain.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] Thus, the WSS assumption is widely employed in signal processing algorithms.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] The concept of stationarity may be extended to two stochastic processes.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] The terminology used for types of stationarity other than strict stationarity can be rather mixed.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] In time series analysis and stochastic processes, stationarizing a time series is a crucial preprocessing step aimed at transforming a non-stationary process into a stationary one.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] Several techniques exist for achieving this, depending on the type and order of non-stationarity present.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] For first-order non-stationarity, where the mean of the process varies over time, differencing is a common and effective method: it transforms the series by subtracting each value from its predecessor, thus stabilizing the mean.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] For non-stationarities up to the second order, time-frequency analysis (e.g., Wavelet transform, Wigner distribution function, or Short-time Fourier transform) can be employed to isolate and suppress time-localized, nonstationary spectral components.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] Additionally, surrogate data methods can be used to construct strictly stationary versions of the original time series.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] One of the ways for identifying non-stationary times series is the ACF plot.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] Sometimes, patterns will be more visible in the ACF plot than in the original time series; however, this is not always the case.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] The choice of method for time series stationarization depends on the nature of the non-stationarity and the goals of the analysis, especially when building models that require strict stationarity assumptions, such as ARMA or spectral-based techniques.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] More details on some time series stationarization methods are presented below.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] One way to make some time series first-order stationary is to compute the differences between consecutive observations.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] Differencing can help stabilize the mean of a time series by removing changes in the level of a time series, and so eliminating trends.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] This can also remove seasonality, if differences are taken appropriately (e.g. differencing observations 1 year apart to remove a yearly trend).
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] Transformations such as logarithms can help to stabilize the variance of a time series.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] The surrogate method for stationarization works by generating a new time series that preserves certain statistical properties of the original series while removing its nonstationary components.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] A common approach is to apply the Fourier Transform to the original time series to obtain its magnitude and phase spectra.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] The magnitude spectrum, which determines the power distribution across frequencies, is retained to preserve the global autocorrelation structure.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] Applying the inverse Fourier Transform to the modified spectra yields a strictly stationary surrogate time series: one with the same power spectrum as the original but lacking the temporal structures that caused non-stationarity.
[src:vector-autoregression/stationary-process] This technique is often used in hypothesis tests for probing the stationarity property.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] Like the autoregressive model, each variable has an equation modelling its evolution over time.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] This equation includes the variable's lagged (past) values, the lagged values of the other variables in the model, and an error term.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] VAR models do not require as much knowledge about the forces influencing a variable as do structural models with simultaneous equations.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] The only prior knowledge required is a list of variables which can be hypothesized to affect each other over time.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] A VAR model describes the evolution of a set of *k* variables, called *endogenous variables*, over time.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] Each period of time is numbered, *t* = 1, ..., *T*.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] The variables are collected in a vector, *yt*, which is of length *k.* (Equivalently, this vector might be described as a (*k* × 1)-matrix.) The vector is modelled as a linear function of its previous value.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] The vector's components are referred to as *y**i*,*t*, meaning the observation at time *t* of the *i* th variable.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] For example, if the first variable in the model measures the price of wheat over time, then *y*1,1998 would indicate the price of wheat in the year 1998.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] VAR models are characterized by their *order*, which refers to the number of earlier time periods the model will use.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] Continuing the above example, a 5th-order VAR would model each year's wheat price as a linear combination of the last five years of wheat prices.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] A *lag* is the value of a variable in a previous time period.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] So in general a *p*th-order VAR refers to a VAR model which includes lags for the last *p* time periods.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] A *p*th-order VAR is denoted "VAR(*p*)" and sometimes called "a VAR with *p* lags".
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] The variables of the form *y**t*−i indicate that variable's value *i* time periods earlier and are called the "i*th* lag" of *y*t.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] The variable *c* is a *k*-vector of constants serving as the intercept of the model.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] *Ai* is a time-invariant (*k* × *k*)-matrix and *e**t* is a *k*-vector of error terms.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] The contemporaneous covariance matrix of error terms is a *k* × *k* positive-semidefinite matrix denoted Ω.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] In particular, there is no serial correlation in individual error terms.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] The process of choosing the maximum lag *p* in the VAR model requires special attention because inference is dependent on correctness of the selected lag order.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] Note that all variables have to be of the same order of integration.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] Each variable in the model has one equation.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] The current (time *t*) observation of each variable depends on its own lagged values as well as on the lagged values of each other variable in the VAR.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] A VAR with *p* lags can always be equivalently rewritten as a VAR with only one lag by appropriately redefining the dependent variable.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] The transformation amounts to stacking the lags of the VAR(*p*) variable in the new VAR(1) dependent variable and appending identities to complete the precise number of equations.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] The equivalent VAR(1) form is more convenient for analytical derivations and allows more compact statements.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] where *c*0 is a *k* × 1 vector of constants, *Bi* is a *k* × *k* matrix (for every *i* = 0, ..., *p*) and *ε**t* is a *k* × 1 vector of error terms.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] The main diagonal terms of the *B*0 matrix (the coefficients on the *i*th variable in the *i*th equation) are scaled to 1.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] The error terms ε*t* (***structural shocks***) satisfy the conditions (1) - (3) in the definition above, with the particularity that all the elements in the off diagonal of the covariance matrix $\mathrm {E} (\epsilon _{t}\epsilon _{t}')=\Sigma$ are zero.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] That is, the structural shocks are uncorrelated.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] that is, the variances of the structural shocks are denoted $\mathrm {var} (\epsilon _{i})=\sigma _{i}^{2}$ (*i* = 1, 2) and the covariance is $\mathrm {cov} (\epsilon _{1},\epsilon _{2})=0$ .
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] Note that *y*2,*t* can have a contemporaneous effect on *y1,t* if *B*0;1,2 is not zero.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] This is different from the case when *B*0 is the identity matrix (all off-diagonal elements are zero — the case in the initial definition), when *y*2,*t* can impact directly *y*1,*t*+1 and subsequent future values, but not *y*1,*t*.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] Because of the parameter identification problem, ordinary least squares estimation of the structural VAR would yield inconsistent parameter estimates.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] This problem can be overcome by rewriting the VAR in reduced form.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] From an economic point of view, if the joint dynamics of a set of variables can be represented by a VAR model, then the structural form is a depiction of the underlying, "structural", economic relationships.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] , which implies zero correlation between error terms as a desired property.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] This is helpful for separating out the effects of economically unrelated influences in the VAR.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] ); therefore one would expect these factors to be statistically independent.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] This is a desirable feature especially when using low frequency data.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] the day the decision is announced, but one could find an effect in that quarter's data.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] Note that in the reduced form all right hand side variables are predetermined at time *t*.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] As there are no time *t* endogenous variables on the right hand side, no variable has a *direct* contemporaneous effect on other variables in the model.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] However, the error terms in the reduced VAR are composites of the structural shocks *e**t* = *B*0−1*ε**t*.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] Thus, the occurrence of one structural shock *εi,t* can potentially lead to the occurrence of shocks in all error terms *ej,t*, thus creating contemporaneous movement in all endogenous variables.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] can have non-zero off-diagonal elements, thus allowing non-zero correlation between error terms.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] where $\otimes$ denotes the Kronecker product and Vec the vectorization of the indicated matrix.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] This estimator is consistent and asymptotically efficient.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] It is furthermore equal to the conditional maximum likelihood estimator.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] As in the standard case, the maximum likelihood estimator (MLE) of the covariance matrix differs from the ordinary least squares (OLS) estimator.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] Vector autoregression models often involve the estimation of many parameters.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] This can hurt the accuracy of the parameter estimates and hence of the forecasts given by the model.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] for evolving (state) vector y and vector e of shocks.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] An estimated VAR model can be used for forecasting, and the quality of the forecasts can be judged, in ways that are completely analogous to the methods used in univariate autoregressive modelling.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] Christopher Sims has advocated VAR models, criticizing the claims and performance of earlier modeling in macroeconomic econometrics.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] He recommended VAR models, which had previously appeared in time series statistics and in system identification, a statistical specialty in control theory.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] Sims advocated VAR models as providing a theory-free method to estimate economic relationships, thus being an alternative to the "incredible identification restrictions" in structural models.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] VAR models are also increasingly used in health research for automatic analyses of diary data or sensor data.
[src:vector-autoregression/structural-vector-autoregression] Caraka found that the artificial neural network can improve its performance with the addition of the hybrid vector autoregression component.
